Note that the exercise does follow from Dirichlet’s theorem for arithmetic progressions, but there are easier proofs.

32.2 Galois Theory of \({\mathbb{Q}}(\zeta_m) / {\mathbb{Q}}\)

Let \(\sigma \in G(K/{\mathbb{Q}})\), then we saw that \(\sigma(\zeta_m) = \zeta_m^a\) for some \(a\) coprime to \(m\). So we know \(\# G(K/{\mathbb{Q}}) < \phi(m)\), since there are only that many possibilities for the right-hand side. Since \([K:{\mathbb{Q}}] = \phi(m)\), for each \(a\) coprime to \(m\) there is a \(\sigma_a\) with \(\sigma_a(\zeta_m) = \zeta_m^a\), so we can write \begin{align*} G(K/{\mathbb{Q}}) = \left\{{ \sigma_a {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}a\in ({\mathbb{Z}}/m)^{\times}}\right\} .\end{align*} Noting that \(\sigma_a \sigma_b (\zeta_m) = \zeta_m^{ab} = \sigma_{ab}\), so we get an isomorphism \begin{align*} G(K/{\mathbb{Q}}) &\xrightarrow{\sim} ({\mathbb{Z}}/m) ^{\times}\\ \sigma_a &\rightleftharpoons a\pmod m ,\end{align*} so \(K/{\mathbb{Q}}\) is an abelian extension.

32.2.1 The Frobenius

Consider \(K \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}={\mathbb{Q}}(\zeta_m)\), then for every rational prime \(P\) unramified in \(K\), there is a well-defined element in \(\qty{K/{\mathbb{Q}}\over P} \in G(K/{\mathbb{Q}}) = ({\mathbb{Z}}/m)^{\times}\). For a given \(P\), which element in \(({\mathbb{Z}}/m)^{\times}\) do you get?

If \(p% \mathrel{\mkern.5mu % small adjustment % superimpose \nmid to \big| \ooalign{\hidewidth$\big|$\hidewidth\cr$\nmid$\cr}% }% m\), then \(p\) is unramified in \({\mathbb{Q}}(\zeta_m)\).

The converse is more or less true: \({\mathbb{Q}}(\zeta_2) = {\mathbb{Q}}\) since \(\zeta_2 = -1\), but 2 is not ramified in \({\mathbb{Q}}\) since nothing is ramified in itself. So if you avoid \(m\equiv 2 \pmod 4\), the converse becomes true. We’ll just prove the mentioned direction.

\begin{align*} {\mathbb{Z}}_K = {\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta_m] .\end{align*}

Show that \(p\) ramifies in \(K\) iff \({\mathbb{Z}}_K/p{\mathbb{Z}}_K\) has a nonzero nilpotent element.

Suppose \(p% \mathrel{\mkern.5mu % small adjustment % superimpose \nmid to \big| \ooalign{\hidewidth$\big|$\hidewidth\cr$\nmid$\cr}% }% m\), then it suffices to show that \({\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta_m] / p{\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta_m]\) has no nonzero nilpotents. Let \(\alpha\in {\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta_m]\) with \(\alpha \pmod p\) nilpotent in the quotient, we’ll show it must be zero in the quotient. By the lemma, we can write \(\alpha = \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta^i\), using that \({\mathbb{Z}}_K = {\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta]\) where all of the \(a_i\) are in \({\mathbb{Z}}\), we’ve set \(\zeta\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\zeta_m\) and \(d = \phi(m) = [K : {\mathbb{Q}}]\).

Look mod \(p\), then \begin{align*} \alpha^p &\equiv \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta^{ip} \pmod p \implies \alpha^{p^f} &\equiv \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta^{ip^f} \pmod p && \forall f .\end{align*} If \(f\) is large enough, \(\alpha^{p^f} \equiv 0 \pmod p\), since some power of \(\alpha\) is zero. On the other hand, \(p% \mathrel{\mkern.5mu % small adjustment % superimpose \nmid to \big| \ooalign{\hidewidth$\big|$\hidewidth\cr$\nmid$\cr}% }% m\), so there are powers of \(p\) that are \(1\pmod m\) that show up regularly, and we can choose \(f\) so that \(p^f \cong 1 \pmod m\), e.g. by choosing \(f\) to be any multiple of the order of \(p\) mod \(m\). But then the second line above reduces to \(\sum a_i\zeta^{ip^f} \equiv \sum a_i \zeta^{i} = \alpha\) since \(p^f \equiv 1 \pmod m\), so \(\alpha^{p^f} \equiv \alpha\), but we know \(\alpha^{p^f} \equiv 0\).

Suppose \(p% \mathrel{\mkern.5mu % small adjustment % superimpose \nmid to \big| \ooalign{\hidewidth$\big|$\hidewidth\cr$\nmid$\cr}% }% m\), which guarantees \(p\) does not ramify in \(K\). Then \begin{align*} \qty{K/{\mathbb{Q}}\over P} = \sigma_p && \sigma_p(\zeta_m) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\zeta_m^p .\end{align*}

Choose any \(Q\) lying above \(p\). We’ll show that for all \(\alpha\in {\mathbb{Z}}_K\), \(\sigma_p( \alpha) = \alpha^p \pmod Q\), which by the characterization theorem will show \(\sigma_p = \mathop{\mathrm{Frob}}_{Q/P}\), and in the abelian case \(\qty{K/{\mathbb{Q}}\over p}\) reduces to this single element. We know that \(Q\supseteq p{\mathbb{Z}}_K\) since \(Q\) is above \(p\), so it’s enough to show \(\sigma_p( \alpha) \equiv \alpha^p \pmod p\) for all \(\alpha\in {\mathbb{Z}}_K\) – this is because the difference is a multiple of \(p\) in \({\mathbb{Z}}_K\), which is a subset of \(Q\). Using \({\mathbb{Z}}_K = {\mathbb{Z}}[\zeta_m]\) to write \(\alpha = \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta_m^{i}\) where \(d\) is the degree of the extension. Now reducing \(\pmod p\) and applying the Freshman’s dream yields \begin{align*} \sigma_p( \alpha) &= \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta_m^{ip} \\ &\equiv \qty{ \sum_{i=0}^{d-1} a_i \zeta_m^{i}}^p \pmod p \\ &\equiv \alpha^p .\end{align*}

This can be used to determine how all of the primes \(p% \mathrel{\mkern.5mu % small adjustment % superimpose \nmid to \big| \ooalign{\hidewidth$\big|$\hidewidth\cr$\nmid$\cr}% }% m\) factor in \({\mathbb{Q}}(\zeta_m)\), i.e. easily determining the relevant values of \(f\) and \(g\).
